body:
Thanks for the script. We want to do bench-marking carefully, as mxnet's execution is asynchronize, measuring the time when backward returns is not precise. So we should be slower than this statistics indicates.

@antinucleon  is working on a benchmark script that takes this into cosideration.

This being said, it is hard for any toolkit to be super faster on a single card, due to the bottleneck passed down into kernel optimizations(where everybody uses CuDNN). More interesting result might be comparing the multiple card version with full updates

Didn't know you could do that.
I set `ulimit -c unlimited` to get a core file to show up,
then gdb that file. all ??? on backtrace, no symbols despite mxnet with -g. I checked each of the 4 available frames and none had symbols.

I think its in the ThreadEnginePerDevice dealloc method.
I annotated the code with the following:

``` c++
    printf("A\n");
    gpu_normal_workers_.Clear();
    printf("B\n");
    gpu_copy_workers_.Clear();
    printf("C\n");
    cpu_normal_workers_.Clear();
    printf("D\n");
    cpu_priority_worker_.reset(nullptr);
    printf("Dealloc threadedEgninginePer\n");
```

With a result of

```
$ MXNET_ENGINE_TYPE=ThreadedEnginePerDevice python test.py 
[16:02:50] src/engine/engine.cc:36: MXNet start using engine: ThreadedEnginePerDevice
A
B
C
D
terminate called after throwing an instance of 'std::system_error'
